---
import BlogPostLayout from '../../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
import { getBlogPost } from '../../lib/blog-posts';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import SteeringLoop from '../../components/SteeringLoop';
import DeclarativeVsImperative from '../../components/DeclarativeVsImperative';
import TriageSpecPlan from '../../components/TriageSpecPlan';
import EvolutionLoop from '../../components/EvolutionLoop';

export const frontmatter = {
  title: 'Autonomous Agents',
  description:
    'Stop steering an LLM three minutes at a time. Make the goal a file, loop on it, and push your judgment to the edges — so an agent runs autonomously in the middle.',
  author: 'Adelphi Liong',
  date: '2026-06-21',
  topic: 'tech' as const,
  tags: ['llm', 'ai', 'agents', 'workflow'],
  shareMessage: 'How to run an LLM autonomously instead of babysitting it all day',
};

const post = getBlogPost('autonomous-agents')!;
---

<BlogPostLayout post={post}>
  <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
    <em
      >You can spend a whole day with an AI coding agent and produce one feature. Not because the work was hard — because
      you never stopped steering. Three minutes prompting, three minutes waiting, a correction, another correction. The
      fix isn't a better prompt. It's a different shape of work: push your judgment to the edges and let the agent run on
      its own in the middle.</em
    >
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The hour you already know</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Here's a typical hour. You ask the agent for a feature — say, a soft-delete endpoint for orders. It comes back with
    something that's about 70% right. The endpoint exists, but it hard-deletes the row instead of flagging it. You point
    that out. It fixes the delete, but now deleted orders 404 on the read path. You correct that. It patches the read
    path, and a list-endpoint test breaks because deleted rows are showing up. You correct again.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Each round is small. Three minutes to write the correction, three minutes to wait for the result. But stack them up
    and the shape becomes obvious: <strong>you are the loop</strong>. The agent never runs more than one step without
    you. You are holding the goal in your head, re-deriving it every turn, nudging the work back on course one sentence
    at a time. That's not delegation. That's manual driving with extra latency.
  </p>

  <SteeringLoop client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    The trap is that every individual turn feels productive. It <em>did</em> do something. It <em>is</em> faster than
    typing the code yourself. So you keep going, and the day evaporates, and at the end you've shipped a ticket you could
    have written by hand in the same time — except now you're tired from context-switching every six minutes.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The shift: work to the front, judgment to the edges</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    There's an old move from functional programming that solves a structurally identical problem. In FP, side effects
    are the dangerous part — reading files, hitting the network, mutating state. The discipline is to push those effects
    to the <em>boundary</em> of the program and keep a <strong>pure core</strong> in the middle: a big, deterministic,
    easy-to-reason-about region with no surprises, wrapped by a thin shell where the messy real-world interaction
    happens.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Running an agent autonomously is the same move. The "side effects" here are the parts that genuinely need a human:
    deciding what to build, judging whether a risky tradeoff is acceptable, reviewing whether the result is any good.
    Push those to the edges. Put <strong>planning and judgment at the front</strong>, <strong
      >autonomous execution in the middle</strong
    >, and <strong>review at the end</strong>. The middle becomes a pure core the agent can grind through without you in
    it.
  </p>

  <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-primary pl-6 py-1 my-6 italic text-muted-foreground">
    Stop steering an LLM three minutes at a time. Make the goal a file, loop on it, and push your judgment to the edges.
  </blockquote>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The payoff isn't only that you stop babysitting. It's that you can take <em>bigger</em> tickets. When your bandwidth
    goes to direction and risk instead of keystroke-level steering, the size of the work you can supervise goes up. You
    spend your attention where it's scarce — deciding and reviewing — and let the cheap, parallelizable part run
    unattended.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Two failure modes, two different fixes</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Before you can automate the middle, you have to understand <em>why</em> an unattended agent goes wrong. There are two
    distinct failure modes, and conflating them is why most "just write a better prompt" advice fails.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Reliability.</strong> The model knows what to do and could do it, but doesn't. It forgets an instruction you
    gave three messages ago. It skips a convention the codebase obviously follows. It declares victory without checking
    its own work. It drifts off the task onto something adjacent. This isn't a thinking problem — it's a
    <em>follow-through</em> problem.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Capability.</strong> The model genuinely can't get there from where it's standing. It reasons badly about the
    problem, builds on a wrong assumption, or brute-forces something that needed insight. More reminders won't help,
    because reminding it isn't the issue — it never had the right footing to begin with.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    These need opposite fixes. Reliability is fixed by <strong>structure</strong>: a fixed goal and a fresh, disciplined
    loop. Capability is fixed by <strong>information</strong>: a spec that gives the model the footing a ticket assumes
    but never states. The <em>why</em> underneath both — why a stable goal shapes better output, why more context changes
    what the model can do — is the subject of
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/probability-space-engineering">Probability Space Engineering</a>.
    This post is the practice; treat that one as the theory it rests on.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Reliability → stateless loops</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Reliability problems come from two sources: a goal that moves, and a context that accumulates baggage. Fix both and
    most "it forgot / it drifted" failures disappear.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Declarative: put the goal in a file</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    A chat is <em>imperative</em>. Each message is an instruction relative to the current state, and the agent steers off
    your <em>last sentence</em>. That's exactly why the morning grind drifts: you said "fix the read path," so it fixed
    the read path and lost track of the list endpoint. The target moved because your instructions are a moving target.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The fix is to make the goal <strong>declarative</strong>: write down the <em>end state</em>, not the keystrokes to
    get there. Put it in a file — call it <code>goal.md</code> — and describe what "done" looks like. A declarative goal
    doesn't move when you stop talking, because it isn't made of your talking.
  </p>

  <DeclarativeVsImperative client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    Notice what the goal file does: it states every part of the end state at once — soft delete sets a flag, reads
    include deleted rows with a marker, the list excludes them by default, tests pass. No single instruction can knock
    the others out, because they're all written down together. The agent re-reads the whole thing every time.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Stateless: every loop starts fresh</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The second source of unreliability is conversational baggage. A long chat carries dead ends, abandoned approaches,
    half-corrected mistakes, and your increasingly frustrated tone — all of which sit in the context and pull on the next
    response. The fix is to make each iteration <strong>stateless</strong>. Every loop starts clean:
  </p>

  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>Read the goal and the current state of the code.</li>
    <li>Make as much progress toward the goal as it can.</li>
    <li>Write evidence of what it did (and what's left).</li>
    <li>Exit.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Then the next iteration starts a fresh context and does the same thing — reading the same fixed goal and whatever
    code now exists. There's no growing transcript to rot. The only state that survives between loops is the goal (which
    doesn't change) and the code (which is the actual work). That's the whole point: the agent's memory <em>is</em> the
    repository, not the conversation.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Why looping beats orchestrating</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    There's a temptation to reach for elaborate multi-agent schemes — agents that collaborate, orchestrate sub-agents,
    negotiate, or vote. They sound sophisticated. They're also a nightmare to build, debug, and reason about, because the
    moment two agents share state you've created a distributed system with all the race conditions and emergent
    weirdness that implies.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    A single looping agent is the opposite. It's one prompt, one file, and one stop condition. You can read the whole
    thing. When it misbehaves, you look at the goal, the code, and the prompt — three concrete things — and you'll find
    the problem. Simplicity isn't a consolation prize here; it's the feature. A loop you understand beats an orchestra
    you don't.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">The mechanics are almost embarrassingly small. The re-used prompt is roughly:</p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    code={`Read goal.md and the current code.

Implement the goal. Verify it is 100% done —
run the tests, check every item in the end state.
If anything is incomplete or broken, fix it.

When you finish, report what you did.
If the goal was already fully met before you
started, reply exactly: ALREADY COMPLETED`}
  />

  <p class="mb-6">
    You run that prompt. The agent works, then exits. A stop-hook fires the same prompt again into a fresh context. It
    works again. This repeats — prompt → stop-hook → prompt → … — until the agent reads the goal, finds everything
    already true, and replies <code>ALREADY COMPLETED</code>. That string is the stop condition. The loop halts.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    code={`loop:
  run prompt (fresh context)
    → agent reads goal + code
    → makes progress, writes evidence, exits
  stop-hook checks the last reply
    → "ALREADY COMPLETED"?  yes → done
                            no  → loop again`}
  />

  <p class="mb-6">
    In practice you collapse all of this behind a single command — a <code>/goal</code>-style entry point that points the
    loop at your goal file and runs it to completion. You write the goal, you type one command, and you walk away. That's
    the autonomous middle: no steering, no babysitting, just a fixed target and a fresh loop grinding toward it.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Capability → specs</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    A reliable loop will faithfully execute a bad plan. So the loop only solves half the problem. The other half is
    making sure the goal it loops on is actually <em>correct</em> — and that's a capability problem, fixed with
    information.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Here's the root issue. A ticket is written <strong>human to human</strong>. It assumes the reader already knows the
    codebase, knows the conventions, knows who to ask, and — crucially — will <em>push back</em> when something is
    ambiguous or wrong. A human engineer reads "add soft delete to orders" and immediately asks: soft delete how? Do
    existing reads need to change? What about the audit log? Does this cascade to order items?
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    An LLM doesn't do that. It won't say "I'm confused." It will <strong>confidently guess</strong>, fill the gaps with
    plausible-sounding assumptions, and present the result as if it were certain. The ticket's missing context didn't
    stop it — it just got silently invented. That's the capability failure: not bad reasoning in a vacuum, but reasoning
    from a blank you never noticed it was filling.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">The fix is to front-load the thinking in three steps, in order.</p>

  <TriageSpecPlan client:load />

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">1. Triage — interrogate the ticket</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Before anything else, surface every assumption, gap, and risk the ticket carries — and fact-check each one against
    the actual code. This is interrogation, not implementation. The agent's job here is to ask the questions a senior
    engineer would ask, then go read the repo to answer as many as it can and flag the rest for you.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">2. Spec — declare what "done" means</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Once the unknowns are resolved, declare the target: a <strong>Definition of Done</strong>. This is behaviour, not
    code. It covers the functional requirements (what it does), the non-functional ones (performance, security,
    compatibility), how each will be validated, and the pre- and post-conditions. No implementation — just an unambiguous
    description of the world after the change. This <em>is</em> the goal file the loop will run on.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">3. Plan — decompose into verifiable slices</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Finally, decompose the spec into <strong>committable, independently verifiable, file-level slices</strong>. Each
    slice is a small unit that can be implemented and checked on its own — ideally one that maps to a clean commit. This
    is what lets the loop make discrete, evidence-backed progress instead of attempting the whole thing in one shapeless
    pass.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The order is not negotiable. You can't write a Definition of Done while your assumptions are still unverified — you'd
    be specifying a fantasy. And you can't decompose into slices before you know what the whole is. Triage feeds spec;
    spec feeds plan. Skip a step and the error propagates into everything downstream.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">Walk the soft-delete example through it:</p>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>
      <strong>Triage</strong> reads the order model and finds there's no <code>deleted_at</code> column, that three read
      endpoints touch orders, and that order items reference orders by foreign key. It flags one open question: should
      deleting an order soft-delete its items too? You answer: no, items stay.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Spec</strong> declares the Definition of Done: a <code>deleted_at</code> column exists; delete sets it;
      single-order reads return deleted orders with a flag; the list endpoint excludes them by default; order items are
      untouched; all existing tests still pass and new tests cover each rule.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan</strong> slices it: (1) migration for the column, (2) the delete handler, (3) the read-path flag, (4)
      the list-endpoint filter, (5) tests. Five commits, each verifiable on its own.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The list-endpoint regression that ate your morning earlier? It was decided in slice 4, on purpose, before a single
    line was written. That's the difference front-loading makes.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The whole package</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Put the two halves together and the picture is clean. <strong>A good plan covers capability</strong> — it gives the
    model the footing the ticket assumed. <strong>A reliable loop covers reliability</strong> — it executes that plan
    without drifting or forgetting. Front-load the thinking; automate the doing. The human is at the front (deciding what
    "done" means) and at the end (judging whether it's any good), and absent from the middle.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">The ticket-to-PR flow falls out of this naturally:</p>

  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li>
      <strong>Plan.</strong> Triage → spec → plan, with you in the loop resolving the open questions. This is where your
      judgment lives.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Implementation.</strong> The stateless loop grinds through the slices unattended. Because the plans are
      file-level and independent, non-conflicting plans can run in <em>parallel</em>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Polish.</strong> A final pass cleans up the seams — naming, dead code, anything the slice-by-slice march
      left rough.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Review.</strong> You review the real PR, the same as any human's. This is the other edge — judgment at the
      boundary, where the side effects live.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The compounding harness</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Your first autonomous runs will be mediocre, and it's worth being honest about why. They'll pass every check you
    wrote and still be <em>off</em>. The agent reinvents a helper that already exists three files over. It over-builds —
    a configurable factory where a function would do. It writes in a house style that isn't yours. The tests are green;
    the taste is wrong.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The important thing is that these are <strong>blind spots, not random noise</strong>. They're systematic — the model
    reliably doesn't know your conventions, because nobody wrote them down where it could see. (This jaggedness, where a
    model is brilliant and oblivious in the same breath, is the subject of
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/jagged-intelligence">Jagged Intelligence</a> — the surface
    you're working around.) A systematic gap is fixable in a way random noise never is: you can name it, and once named,
    you can close it.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">The evolution meta-loop</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    So you build a second loop around the first one — a loop that improves the harness itself. After a run, you don't
    just fix the output and move on. You feed the lesson back in:
  </p>

  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>Give feedback</strong> on what was off ("it built a helper that duplicates the existing one").</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ask the model to extract the underlying rule</strong> — not the one-off fix, but the general principle
      ("check for an existing utility before writing a new one").
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Backtest the rule against the existing codebase.</strong> Does it actually hold? Search the repo: do
      engineers really reuse utilities here, or is duplication common? If the rule holds, keep it. If it doesn't, refine
      or reject it — a rule that contradicts the codebase will do more harm than the blind spot did.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Fold confirmed rules into the rules layer</strong> — <code>CLAUDE.md</code> and its friends — where every
      future run will read them.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <EvolutionLoop client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    The next run starts better, because it starts with the rule already in context. And it generates new, subtler blind
    spots, which you extract, backtest, and fold in turn. The system <strong>compounds</strong>: each pass tightens the
    harness, and the harness shapes the next pass. You're not just shipping features — you're teaching the machine your
    codebase, permanently, one verified rule at a time.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">A closing caution: more output, more bugs</h3>

  <p class="mb-6">
    One honest note to end on. Even as your per-line accuracy climbs, your <em>absolute</em> bug count can rise — simply
    because you're producing far more code. It's the taxi-driver problem: a careful driver who drives ten times as far
    will, in raw numbers, have more incidents than a reckless one who barely leaves the driveway, even though they're
    safer per mile. Throughput multiplies everything, including mistakes.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The answer isn't to slow down — it's to build the review and the rules layer to <em>match</em> the throughput. The
    edges have to scale with the middle. A loud, fast middle with a thin review boundary just ships bugs faster. Invest
    in the front (better specs) and the end (real review and a compounding rules layer) in proportion to how much you let
    the middle run. Done right, that's the whole bet of autonomous agents: front-load the judgment, automate the doing,
    and let the harness get smarter every time you use it.
  </p>

  <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground mb-3">Related</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-muted-foreground">
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/probability-space-engineering"
          >Probability Space Engineering</a
        > — why these moves work
      </li>
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/jagged-intelligence">Jagged Intelligence</a> — the surface you're
        working around
      </li>
      <li>
        <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/how-llms-work">How LLMs Actually Work</a> — the input/context
        primer
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
